<HEADLINE>
<P>
GOLF; KITE, SUTTON TIED FOR LEAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A two-shot swing on the final hole Thursday left Tom Kite and Hal Sutton tied 
for the lead at six-under-par 66 in the first round of the $1.2-million 
BellSouth Classic. 
</P>
<P>
 Kite, the 1992 U.S. Open champion and winner of this event the same year, 
rolled in a five-foot birdie putt and Sutton, winless since the 1986 Memorial, 
had his only bogey of the day after he missed the ninth green. 
</P>
<P>
 Both Kite and Sutton began play on the hilly, 7,018-yard Atlanta Country Club 
course on No. 10. 
</P>
<P>
 They held their one-shot lead over Craig Parry, whose bogey-free round 
featured birdie putts of 30 feet on No. 4 and 20 feet on No. 13. 
</P>
<P>
 Seven others were at 68 -- Lennie Clements, Paul Goydos, Corey Pavin, Brian 
Henninger, Mark Wurtz, Esteban Toledo and Wayne Levi, a two-time Atlanta 
winner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
