<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By David Haldan; Kevin Johnson, ; Dennis McClellan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 RETURNING FAVOR: Vladimir A. Yakovlev, deputy mayor of St. Petersburg, Russia, 
told officials he saw something on a recent Orange County trip that he'd rarely 
seen in Russian local government: a woman, specifically Supervisor Harriett M. 
Wieder, sitting in a position of political prominence. . . . Impressed, 
Yakovlev gave Wieder a medallion recognizing her "courage to participate in 
local government." The medallion bears the image of Catherine the Great, 
Russia's empress in the late 1700s. The only rub: the county's gift ban forced 
her to give it back. 
</P>
<P>
 LAST LAUGH: Students at Rancho Alamitos High School in Garden Grove have 
decided to give their teachers a break. . . . In honor of next week's national 
Day of the Teacher, a student group persuaded the comedy club Brea Improv to 
give all 100 of the school's teachers and staffers free tickets to a 
performance there. Quips Lynn Hamtil, a school district trustee: "Is this 
supposed to mean teachers do or do not have a sense of humor?" 
</P>
<P>
 NAME GAME: Author Sue Grafton titles her mysteries with letters from the 
alphabet ("A is for Alibi"); Neil Albert uses months. Fountain Valley author 
Earlene Fowler, above, is taking another tack: quilt patterns. . . . Her latest 
book, "Fool's Puzzle," is the first of many she plans on naming after patterns 
well-known to quilters. Says the author, "I used to quilt; now I write." 
</P>
<P>
 ON TARGET: Speaking of writers, Huntington Beach author Robert Peters -- who 
wants to start a workshop for local gay and lesbian writers (E1) -- once met 
his literary hero William Burroughs on the legendary author's Kansas farm. . . 
. At the time, Burroughs was painting canvases, which he shot full of bullet 
holes and then sold to art galleries. After watching Burroughs unload his 
pistol that day, Peters picked up the empty shells and later wrote a memoir of 
his Kansas encounter, 15 copies of which were reproduced "complete with spent 
bullet casings" glued to their title pages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA050694-0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 039016 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
May 6, 1994, Friday, Ventura West Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 1; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
336 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth R. Weiss 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 ROBBING PETER: County elections officials are recruiting volunteers to staff 
the polls for free this June election to help save money (B1). . . . But now 
county library officials want their own volunteers to work the polls so that 
the $55-per-worker stipends can be diverted to the library budget. The Friends 
of the Library and other booster groups have 2,000 members, according to a 
library statement, adding that "if only 20% of these volunteers . . . 
participate in the Tuesday, June 7, election, this would translate into $20,000 
for the library." 
</P>
<P>
 FULL EMPLOYMENT: Last year, county Supervisor Maria VanderKolk cut the salary 
and hours of her aides by 10% to avoid staff cuts suffered by most county 
departments. Last week, she reinstated their salaries in full. At the same 
time, she volunteered her aides to help out with the workload of county 
administrators. "Since they are short-staffed, I'm saying that my staff can 
help out," VanderKolk said. . . . She wants to keep her staff busy as she winds 
down her term in office in coming months. "I didn't want them to be bored. I 
wanted them to be challenged." 
</P>
<P>
 NEW BRASS: In change-of-command ceremonies this morning, Capt James L. Delker 
will relieve Rear Adm. David J. Nash as commanding officer of the Naval 
Construction Battalion Center in Port Hueneme. . . . With the command change, 
neither of Ventura County's Navy bases will have an admiral to look out for 
local interests in endless budget battles. The admiral's job at Point Mugu was 
transferred to China Lake base last year. 
</P>
<P>
 SAYONARA: When seeking delays in criminal cases, some defendants might ask a 
judge to grant them a week or two or perhaps even a month. . . . But this week, 
Bruce M. Alexander of Port Hueneme persuaded the judge to postpone his felony 
drunk-driving case until Jan. 5, 1995. Alexander, a Seabee, immediately shipped 
out for a seven-month tour of duty in Okinawa; budget-strapped prosecutors 
could ill afford to spend the $1,000 for a plane ticket to fly him back. 
</P>
</TEXT>
