<HEADLINE>
<P>
CAREER FAIR EXPLAINS YOUTH JOB OPTIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Simi Valley teen-agers looking for a summer job will have a chance Saturday to 
meet with prospective employers and learn about career options. 
</P>
<P>
 Fifty-two employers from eastern Ventura County are expected to attend the 
city's eighth annual Youth Employment Service Job and Career Fair from 10:30 
a.m. to 1:30 p.m. at Mountain Gate Plaza at Los Angeles Avenue and 1st Street. 
</P>
<P>
 Last year, about 1,000 people between the ages of 16 and 22 participated. 
Organizers expect at least the same turnout this year. 
</P>
<P>
 Among the businesses that will be represented are retail stores, insurance 
companies, modeling agencies, fast-food restaurants, the military and law 
enforcement. 
</P>
<P>
 Organizer Sandra Thompson said about half the businesses are recruiting for 
summer and full-time positions, while the others offer information on career 
opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
 For students who haven't already lined up summer work, Thompson said the job 
fair is a good place to start. 
</P>
<P>
 "We always have a big rush of people calling us the day school's out saying, 
'I want to work this summer,' but then it's too late," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 For best results, Thompson said teen-agers should come prepared to fill out 
applications that ask for previous job experience, Social Security number, 
school information and personal references. 
</P>
</TEXT>
