<TEXT>
<P>
 Money Supply Declines: The Federal Reserve Board reported that the measure of 
the nation's money supply known as M2 fell in the week ended April 25 to a 
seasonally adjusted $3,585.0 billion, down $6.3 billion from a revised $3,591.3 
billion the week before.An even broader measure, M3, fell $12.5 billion to a 
seasonally adjusted $4,214.9 billion from a revised $4,227.4 billion. The 
narrowest measure, M1, fell to $1,136.3, down $1.3 billion from $1,137.6 
billion. M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts and 
non-bank traveler's checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts such as savings deposits and 
money market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid accounts, such as 
certificates of deposit in minimum denominations of $100,000. 
</P>
