<HEADLINE>
<P>
DISK DRIVE MAKER LAYS OFF 103 AT ANAHEIM PLANT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Seagate Technology Corp., the world's largest maker of disk drives for 
personal computers, said Thursday it has laid off 103 workers at its Orange 
County plant. 
</P>
<P>
 Claire West, spokeswoman at Seagate's headquarters in Scotts Valley in 
Northern California, said the company is phasing out older products at the 
Anaheim plant, which makes the aluminum disks that serve as the basic storage 
components in disk drives. 
</P>
<P>
 "Business is good for our products but we decided to phase out this line," she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Earlier this week, Seagate laid off 60 full-time employees and 43 temporary 
workers, West said. The workers built Seagate's eight-inch hard disk products. 
The plant remains open and will focus on building newer technologies that don't 
require as much labor. 
</P>
<P>
 Seagate has more than 40,000 employees worldwide. It acquired the Anaheim 
plant in November, 1987, from Aeon Corp. 
</P>
